1. Introduction

Problem Statement¶

  • In this project, we are making a comparison between Adidas and Nike sneakers products.

Objective¶

  • Our objective is to gain insights and perform opinion mining from the dataset and answer the mining questions.

Mining Questions¶

1. What is the shape of the dataset?

  • The shape of the dataset is (3268, 8).

2. Are there any missing values in this dataset?

  • There no zero missing values in this dataset.

3. List all 8 columns' dtypes.

  • Brand Name - object
  • Product ID - object
  • Listing Price - int64
  • Sale Price - int64
  • Discount - int64
  • Brand - object
  • Rating - float64
  • Reviews - int64

4. Are there any duplicated rows (observations) in this dataset?

  • Yes, there are 88 duplicated rows in this dataset.

5. Refer to the statistical summary of the dataset and answer the following:

  • The average listing price:
    • 6992.71
  • The average sale price:
    • 6027.74
  • The average discount:
    • 27.62
  • The average rating:
    • 3.27
  • The average number of reviews:
    • 41.53

6. Which "Brand" has the highest number of products in this dataset?

  • The brand with the highest number of products is Adidas CORE / NEO.

7. As you can see, the "Listing Price" for some products is zero (0). How many products with zero listing price are there in this dataset?

  • There are 362 number of products that have the Listing Price of 0 in this dataset.

8. Perform the "Univariate EDA", and examine any type of skewness (outliers) for all the variables.

  • Distribution of Sale Price variable is skewed to right.
  • Distribution of Rating variable is skewed to left.
  • Distribution of Reviews count variable is slightely skewed to right.
  • Distribution of Listing Price variable is skewed to right.
  • Distribution of Discount variable is skewed to left.

9. The the percentage for the following:

  • Products with listing prices less than 15000
    • 93.93% products have listing prices less than 15000.
  • Products with sale price less than 15000
    • 96.04% products have sale price less than 15000.
  • Products with at least 50% discount
    • There are 994 products with 50% discount.
    • There are 1055 products with 50% and above discount (atleast 50%).
    • 33.18% products have at least 50% discount.
  • Products with rating less than 3.5
    • 47.12% products have rating less than 3.5.
  • Products with review numbers less than 100
    • 99.93% products have reviews less than 100.
  • The 3 highest percentages of the discount graph
    • Most of the products (approx 1200) have 0% discount.
    • Second highest discount percentage is 50%.
    • The third highest discount percentage is 40% (approx 760 products).

10. Perform the "Bivariate EDA", and examine the following:

  • The two highly positively correlated variables.

    • Sale Price and Listing Price have a highest positive correlation. This is visible in the Scatter plot of these two variables as well as the heat map (correlation value 0.37). It is also logically correct- if a product had high Listing Price, its Sale Price would also be high.

  • The two highly negatively correlated variables

    • Discount and Sale Price are at top of having negative correlation (correlation value = -0.6). This is also visible in their pointplot. Higher the discount offered on a product, lower would be it Sale Price.

Data Description¶

We have a dataset named 'sneakers.csv'

  • Product Name: Name of the product.
  • Product ID: ID of the product.
  • Listing Price: Listed price of the product.
  • Sale Price: Sale price of the product.
  • Discount: Percentage of discount on the product.
  • Brand: Brand of the product.
  • Rating: Rating of the product.
  • Reviews: Number of reviews for the product.

Notes:

  1. NumPy is a library for processing numerical data and is widely used in data science for mathematical operations.
  2. Pandas is a library for data manipulation and analysis, and is often used for cleaning, transforming, and exploring datasets.
  3. Matplotlib is a popular data visualization library that provides a wide range of options for creating different types of plots, charts, and graphs.
  4. Seaborn is a data visualization library based on Matplotlib, which provides high-level interface for creating attractive and informative statistical graphics
  5. The warnings module is being used to suppress any warnings that may appear during the execution of the code.
  6. The PIL stands for Python Imaging Library, and it is a module in Python that provides the capabilities to open, manipulate, and save different image file formats. The Image module is a submodule of PIL that provides a class with the same name that represents a PIL image. It allows us to perform different operations on images, including cropping, resizing, rotating, and converting between different formats.

We see the last five rows with all information about movies such as Product Name, Product ID, Listing Price, Sale Price, Discount, Brand, Rating, Reviews..

In other words, there are 3268 pairs of sneakers in the dataset, and for each pair of sneakers, there are 8 features or attributes recorded, such as Product Name, Product ID, Listing Price, Sale Price, Discount, Brand, Rating, Reviews
  4. sneakers.size is a property of the Pandas DataFrame housing which returns the total number of elements in the DataFrame. In this case, it returns the total number of cells (rows x columns) in the DataFrame housing, which is 26144.
  5. sneakers.ndim is an attribute in Pandas that returns the number of dimensions or axes of the DataFrame. In this case, it returns 2, which means the DataFrame has 2 dimensions (rows and columns).
  6. sneakers.info() is a pandas DataFrame method that provides information about the dataset, such as the number of non-null values, data types of each column, and memory usage. From the output, we can see that the dataset has 3268 rows (entries) and 8 columns, with no missing values in any columns. The data types of the columns include float64 (1 column), int64 (4 columns), and object (3 columns). The float64 data type is used for continuous numerical data, int64 for discrete numerical data, and object for text or mixed numeric and non-numeric data. The memory usage of the dataset is also displayed, which can be helpful when working with large datasets to optimize memory usage.
  7. The sneakers.describe().T method returns a table of descriptive statistics for the numerical columns in the sneakers dataset. Each row represents a different numerical column, and the columns of the table represent:
    • count: the number of non-null values in the column
    • mean: the average value of the column
    • std: the standard deviation of the values in the column
    • min: the minimum value in the column
    • 25%: the 25th percentile of the values in the column
    • 50%: the median value of the column (i.e., the 50th percentile)
    • 75%: the 75th percentile of the values in the column
    • max: the maximum value in the column For example, we can see that the 'Listing Price' column has a mean value of 6868.02 and a standard deviation of 4724.66, with a minimum value of 0 and a maximum value of 29999. The 'Sale Price' column has a mean value of 6134.27 and a standard deviation of 4293.25, with a minimum value of 449 and a maximum value of 36500. Similarly, we can see statistics for other columns like 'Discount', 'Rating', and 'Reviews'.
  8. The code sneakers.isnull().sum() checks for null values in each column of the 'sneakers' DataFrame using the isnull() method, and then sums up the total number of null values in each column using the sum() method. The resulting output shows the number of null values for each column. In this case, there are no null values in any of the columns: 'Product Name', 'Product ID', 'Listing Price', 'Sale Price', 'Discount', 'Brand', 'Rating', and 'Reviews'. Having null values in a dataset can be problematic for data analysis as they can cause errors or lead to inaccurate results. Therefore, it is important to handle null values appropriately before analyzing the data. This may involve removing the null values, imputing them with other values, or using statistical techniques to fill in missing data.
  9. The code sneakers.columns retrieves the list of column names from the 'sneakers' DataFrame using the columns attribute. The output shows the column names of the 'sneakers' DataFrame, which include 'Product Name', 'Product ID', 'Listing Price', 'Sale Price', 'Discount', 'Brand', 'Rating', and 'Reviews'. This information is useful when working with a DataFrame as it allows you to reference individual columns using their names instead of their position in the DataFrame. Notes:

  1. sneakers.duplicated().sum() In the code snippet provided, sneakers is a Pandas DataFrame that contains data about sneakers. The duplicated() method of Pandas DataFrame checks whether each row in the DataFrame is a duplicate of a previous row. Calling duplicated() without any arguments returns a Boolean Series where True represents that a row is a duplicate and False represents that a row is not a duplicate. By calling the sum() method on this Series, we count the number of rows that are marked as duplicates. In this case, the output 88 indicates that there are 88 duplicated rows in the sneakers DataFrame. It may be necessary to remove these duplicates from the dataset in order to avoid any bias in the analysis or modeling.
  2. sneakers[sneakers.duplicated()].count() This code checks for duplicated rows in the sneakers DataFrame. Since the count of duplicated rows is 88, it means that there are 88 rows that are exact duplicates of each other. The result of the second code shows that there are 88 duplicated values in each column of the DataFrame, which corresponds to the 88 duplicated rows found in the previous step. In summary, the DataFrame contains 88 duplicated rows and 88 duplicated values in each column of the DataFrame.
  3. The code sneakers['Sale Price'].nunique() returns the number of unique values in the 'Sale Price' column of the sneakers dataframe. In this case, it returns a value of 227, which means that there are 227 unique sale prices in the 'Sale Price' column. This could imply that there is a wide range of prices for the sneakers, which might require further investigation to understand the factors that influence the sale prices.
  4. The code sneakers.sort_values('Discount', ascending = True ) sorts the 'sneakers' DataFrame based on the 'Discount' column in ascending order using the 'sort_values()' function. It rearranges the rows in such a way that the row with the smallest discount is displayed first, and the row with the largest discount is displayed last. The 'ascending' parameter is set to True, which means that the values are sorted in ascending order (from smallest to largest). The output displays the sorted DataFrame, where the first row shows a discount of 0, indicating that there is no discount, and the last row contains a discount of 60, which is the maximum discount in the dataset.
  5. The code sneakers = sneakers.rename(columns={'ID': 'Brand ID', 'Product Name': 'Brand Name'}) renames two columns in the sneakers DataFrame, using the rename() function. The columns parameter takes a dictionary where the keys are the old column names and the values are the new column names. Specifically, it renames the column ID to Brand ID, and Product Name to Brand Name. This is done to make the column names more descriptive and understandable, as the new names provide more information about what each column represents.
  6. The query query_result = sneakers.query('Sale Price <= 4000 and Rating > 4.0') is filtering the 'sneakers' DataFrame based on two conditions: Sale Price being less than or equal to 4000 and Rating being greater than 4.0. The resulting new DataFrame is named 'query_result'. The resulting DataFrame 'query_result' has 463 rows and 8 columns, namely Brand Name, Product ID, Listing Price, Sale Price, Discount, Brand, Rating, and Reviews. The conditions of the query have filtered out sneakers that have a sale price of more than 4000 and have a rating of less than or equal to 4.0. Hence, the resulting DataFrame 'query_result' only contains sneakers that are priced lower and have good ratings.

Examining the distribution based on mean and median¶

In [54]:
# 1. size of my plot
plt.figure(figsize = (20, 10))

# 2. background color

plt.hist(sneak_pr, color = 'g')

# 3. calculation for the mean ()

plt.axvline (sneak_pr.mean(), color = 'r', linewidth = 1)

# 4. calculation for the median ()

plt.axvline (sneak_pr.median(), color = 'b', linewidth = 3);

Notes:

  1. plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10)) is a function in the matplotlib library that creates a new figure with a specified size. In this case, the size is set to 20 inches for the width and 10 inches for the height using the figsize parameter. By increasing the size of the figure, you can make the plot larger and easier to read. The resulting plot will have a larger x-axis and y-axis, which may make it easier to see small variations in the data. Additionally, the larger size may be helpful when presenting the data to others or including it in a report.
  2. plt.hist(sneak_pr, color='g') This sets the color of the histogram bars to green. The color parameter in plt.hist() function specifies the color of the bars in the histogram. In this case, the color green (short code 'g') is used.
  3. plt.axvline(sneak_pr.mean(), color='r', linewidth=1) This adds a vertical line to the histogram plot at the position of the mean of the 'Sale Price' variable. The line color is set to red (color='r') and the line width is set to 1 (linewidth=1). The purpose of this is to visually indicate the location of the mean value in the distribution of the 'Sale Price' variable.
  4. plt.axvline(sneak_pr.median(), color='b', linewidth=3); This code snippet adds a vertical line to the histogram plot at the position of the median value of the 'sneak_pr' variable. The line color is set to blue (short code 'b') and the line width is set to 3. The purpose of this is to visualize where the median of the 'sneak_pr' variable lies relative to the distribution of the variable.
  5. Based on the histogram plot, we can see that the 'Listing Price' variable in the sneakers dataset is right-skewed with a few outliers on the higher end of the distribution. The majority of sneakers in the dataset have a price between 0 and 8000 dollars, with a mean listing price of approximately 7000 dollars and a median price of approximately 6000 dollars. The histogram also shows that the data is not evenly distributed across the bins. Most of the data points are in the lower end of the distribution. The use of a histogram plot and the addition of the mean and median lines helps us better understand the central tendency and distribution of the 'Listing Price' variable in the dataset.

    2. The variables in the dataset are listed on both the x-axis and y-axis of the heatmap. The color of each cell in the heatmap represents the strength of the correlation coefficient between the corresponding pair of variables. The cell color can range from blue (negative correlation) to red (positive correlation) with white representing no correlation.
    3. The annot=True parameter in the sns.heatmap() function is adding numerical values to each cell of the heatmap. These values represent the correlation coefficients between the variables, which can range from -1 (perfect negative correlation) to 1 (perfect positive correlation).
    4. By examining the heatmap, we can see which variables have strong positive or negative correlations with each other. For example, we can see that the 'Sale Price' variable is strongly positively correlated with the 'Listing Price' variable, indicating that sneakers with higher listing prices tend to sell for higher prices. Similarly, we can see that the 'Discount' variable is positively correlated to 'Ratings' and 'Reviews'.

5. Conclusion

  1. The sneaker dataset consists of 5 different models from the Adidas and Nike brands.
  2. The sale prices range from 499.0 to 36500.0, with discounts ranging from 40 to 60 percent off the original listing price.
  3. Among the 5 models, the NMD_Racer Primeknit Shoes have the highest original listing price, while the Swim Puka Slippers have the lowest.
  4. The NMD_Racer Primeknit Shoes and the Sport Inspired Questar Ride Shoes have the highest ratings among the 5 models, with ratings of 4.8 and 4.1 respectively.
  5. The Taekwondo Shoes have the highest number of reviews, with 72 reviews, while the Sleek Shoes have the lowest, with only 24 reviews.
  6. The sneaker dataset provides a snapshot of some popular Adidas models and their prices and ratings, which could be useful for consumers looking to purchase Adidas sneakers. However, the dataset only includes 5 models, so it may not be representative of the entire Adidas product line, and additional data would be needed for a more comprehensive analysis.
  7. We can observe that Nike does not offer any discount for its products in this dataset.
  8. Adidas ORIGINALS has the discount marked a little over 30%.
  9. Adidas SPORT PERFORMANCE has the highest discount of 40% on its products.
  10. Adidas has 1966 product entries that have discount values > 0 and Nike has 0 product entries that have discount values > 0. Hence Adidas as a brand offers more discounts than Nike.
  11. The distribution of Sale Price variable is skewed to right, distribution of Rating variable is skewed to left, distribution of Reviews count variable is slightely skewed to right, distribution of Listing Price variable is skewed to right, and distribution of Discount variable is skewed to left.
  12. There are 362 number of products that have the Listing Price of 0 in this dataset.
  13. The brand with the highest number of products is Adidas CORE / NEO.
  14. Sale Price and Discount have a negative correlation except a single upward trend, as Discount increases, the Sale Price decreases.
  15. There are no missing values in our dataset.
  16. Before dropping the rows we had 88 duplicated rows.
